    87‚Üí### ky(input, options?)
    88‚Üí
    89‚ÜíThe `input` and `options` are the same as [`fetch`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/WindowOrWorkerGlobalScope/fetch), with additional `options` available (see below).
    90‚Üí
    91‚ÜíReturns a [`Response` object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Response) with [`Body` methods](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Fetch_API/Using_Fetch#body) added for convenience. So you can, for example, call `ky.get(input).json()` directly without having to await the `Response` first. When called like that, an appropriate `Accept` header will be set depending on the body method used. Unlike the `Body` methods of `window.Fetch`, these will throw an `HTTPError` if the response status is not in the range of `200...299`. Also, `.json()` will return an empty string if body is empty or the response status is `204` instead of throwing a parse error due to an empty body.
    92‚Üí
    93‚ÜíAvailable body shortcuts: `.json()`, `.text()`, `.formData()`, `.arrayBuffer()`, `.blob()`, and `.bytes()`. The `.bytes()` shortcut is only present when the runtime supports `Response.prototype.bytes()`.
    94‚Üí
    95‚Üí```js
    96‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
    97‚Üí
    98‚Üíconst user = await ky('/api/user').json();
    99‚Üí
   100‚Üíconsole.log(user);
   101‚Üí```
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   123‚Üí### ky.post(input, options?)
   124‚Üí### ky.put(input, options?)
   125‚Üí### ky.patch(input, options?)
   126‚Üí### ky.head(input, options?)
   127‚Üí### ky.delete(input, options?)
   128‚Üí
   129‚ÜíSets `options.method` to the method name and makes a request.
   130‚Üí
   131‚Üí‚å®Ô∏è **TypeScript:** Accepts an optional type parameter for use with JSON responses (see [`ky()`](#kyinput-options)).
   132‚Üí
  1052‚Üí### Sending form data
  1053‚Üí
  1054‚ÜíSending form data in Ky is identical to `fetch`. Just pass a [`FormData`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/FormData) instance to the `body` option. The `Content-Type` header will be automatically set to `multipart/form-data`, overriding any existing `Content-Type` header.
  1055‚Üí
  1056‚Üí```js
  1057‚Üíimport ky from 'ky';
  1058‚Üí
  1059‚Üí// `multipart/form-data`
  1060‚Üíconst formData = new FormData();
  1061‚ÜíformData.append('food', 'fries');
  1062‚ÜíformData.append('drink', 'icetea');
  1063‚Üí
  1064‚Üíconst response = await ky.post(url, {body: formData});
  1065‚Üí```
  1066‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
  1158‚Üí#### Native proxy support
  1159‚Üí
  1160‚ÜíNode.js 24.5+ supports automatic proxy configuration via environment variables. Set `NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY=1` or use the `--use-env-proxy` CLI flag.
  1161‚Üí
  1162‚Üí```sh
  1163‚ÜíNODE_USE_ENV_PROXY=1 HTTP_PROXY=http://proxy.example.com:8080 node app.js
  1164‚Üí```
  1165‚Üí
  1166‚ÜíOr:
  1167‚Üí
  1168‚Üí```sh
  1169‚Üínode --use-env-proxy app.js
  1170‚Üí```
  1171‚Üí
  1172‚ÜíSupported environment variables:
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
  1294‚Üí#### How do I use this in Node.js?
  1295‚Üí
  1296‚ÜíNode.js 18 and later supports `fetch` natively, so you can just use this package directly.
  1297‚Üí
